🌐 Routing Fundamentals
🔹 What is Routing?

        Routing = ek process jisme data packets ko ek network se dusre network tak best path use karke bheja jata hai.
        👉 Router ek postman ki tarah hota hai jo dekhta hai ki packet (letter) ko kahan bhejna hai aur konsa rasta best hai.

🔹 Why Routing is Needed?

        Agar sirf ek hi network ho (jaise ek ghar ka LAN) → Routing ki need nahi.
        
        Lekin jab multiple networks ko connect karna ho (jaise College LAN → Internet → Company LAN), tab Routing zaroori hai.
        
        Router ke bina packet ko pata hi nahi chalega kaha jana hai.

🔹 Router ka Kaam kya hota hai?

        Path Decide karna (Best route find karna)
        
        Packets Forward karna (Source → Destination)
        
        Loop avoid karna (jaise ek hi packet baar-baar ghoom na jaye)
        
        Network divide karna (alag-alag broadcast domain banata hai)

🔹 Routing Table

        Router ke paas ek Routing Table hoti hai = ek "Map" jisme likha hota hai ki kaunsa destination kis rasta se reachable hai.
        
        Jaise postman ke paas ek address book hoti hai.
        
        Example Entry:
        
                Destination: 192.168.1.0/24 → Next Hop: 10.0.0.2 via FastEthernet0/0

🔹 Types of Routing
1. Static Routing

        Admin manually route dalta hai.
        
        Simple, secure, lekin agar network bada ho to manage karna mushkil.
        
        Example:
        
                ip route 192.168.2.0 255.255.255.0 10.0.0.2


👉 Matlab agar packet 192.168.2.0 network ke liye hai to usko 10.0.0.2 pe bhej do.

2. Dynamic Routing

        Routers automatically routes discover karte hain using Routing Protocols.
        
        Example: RIP, OSPF, EIGRP, BGP.
        
        Advantage → Auto updates, best path choose hota hai.
        
        Example (OSPF me):
        
                router ospf 1
                network 192.168.1.0 0.0.0.255 area 0

🔹 Routing Protocols ke Examples

        | Protocol | Type            | Metric (Best Path Kaise Decide karta hai)   |
        | -------- | --------------- | ------------------------------------------- |
        | RIP      | Distance Vector | Hop Count (max 15 hops)                     |
        | OSPF     | Link State      | Cost (Bandwidth based)                      |
        | EIGRP    | Hybrid          | Bandwidth + Delay                           |
        | BGP      | Path Vector     | AS Path (Internet backbone me use hota hai) |

🔹 Key Routing Concepts

Hop Count → Ek packet kitne routers cross karta hai.
        (Jaise ek city se doosri city jane ke liye kitne toll booths aaye).

Administrative Distance (AD) → Reliability measure.

        Static route ka AD = 1 (sabse reliable)
        
        RIP = 120, OSPF = 110, EIGRP = 90

Default Route → Agar unknown destination ho to ek "last option" path.

        ip route 0.0.0.0 0.0.0.0 10.0.0.1


👉 Matlab sab unknown traffic ko 10.0.0.1 pe bhej do.

🔹 Real Life Example (Relatable)

        Tu apne city (LAN) se ek dost ke ghar (dusra network) jana chahta hai.
        
        Tere paas map (routing table) hai jisme likha hai kahan se jana hai.
        
        Agar ek hi route ho → Static Routing (sirf wahi road le sakta hai).
        
        Agar multiple roads ho → Tu GPS (Dynamic Routing) use karega jo best/fastest route batata hai.

📝 Summary:

        Routing = Best path choose + Packet forward karna.
        
        Static Routing → Manual, simple, secure.
        
        Dynamic Routing → Auto, scalable, uses protocols.

        Important concepts = Routing Table, AD, Hop Count, Default Route.
